Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Halve, peel, and thinly slice @yellow onion{1}. Finely dice @Roma tomatoes{2}. Mince @garlic{2%cloves}. Finely chop @parsley{¼%ounce} leaves and stems. Halve @ciabatta bread{1}.

Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{2%tsp} in a #large pot{} over medium-high heat. Add onion, a pinch of @salt{}, and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until softened, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Add tomatoes, @tomato paste{1.5%oz}, @Tuscan Heat Spice{1%tbsp}, half the garlic, and half the parsley. Cook, stirring occasionally, until soft and fragrant, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in @seafood stock concentrate{1}, @chicken stock concentrate{1}, @white wine vinegar{5%tsp}, and 2 1⁄2 cups water (4 cups for 4 servings) to pot with veggies; season with 1 tsp salt (2 tsp for 4) and pepper. Bring to a boil, then reduce heat to medium; simmer until slightly thickened, ~{8-10%minutes}.

== Garlic Toast ==

Meanwhile, place remaining garlic, @butter{2%tbsp} (4 TBSP for 4 servings), and a pinch of salt in a small #microwave-safe bowl{}. Microwave until butter is melted, about ~{30%seconds}.

Place ciabatta, cut sides up, on a #baking sheet{} and brush cut sides with garlic butter. Toast on top rack until crisp and golden, ~{5%minutes}. Slice each ciabatta half on a diagonal to create triangles.

== Cioppino ==

Rinse @shrimp{10%oz} and @scallops{10%oz} under cold water, then pat dry with #paper towels{}.

Add shrimp to pot with stew; simmer until opaque and cooked through, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add scallops; simmer until opaque and cooked through, ~{1-2%minutes} more. Remove pot from heat. Season with salt and pepper.

Divide cioppino between #bowls{}. Garnish with remaining parsley. Serve with garlic toast on the side.

> This Italian-American stew was originally created in the 1800s by fishermen in San Francisco. If there were any leftovers from the day's seafood catch, they were simmered together with tomatoes and wine to create a warming stew. Our version features shrimp and scallops in a Tuscan-style tomato broth, with garlic butter toast on the side for dipping. Cioppino is designed with sharing in mind, so reel your friends in with this savory dish that's sure to have everyone hooked!